-----------------Route Annotations-----------------------

Route Annotations in OpenShift
What are Route Annotations?

Route Annotations are key-value pairs that modify the behavior of an OpenShift Route without changing the application or Service.

They are mainly used to configure the HAProxy Router, which handles incoming traffic to your applications.

Think of annotations as advanced settings for a Route.

General syntax:
oc annotate route <route-name> <annotation-key>=<value>

To view annotations:
oc describe route <route-name>

or

oc get route <route-name> -o yaml
1. Timeout Annotation
Purpose

Controls how long the HAProxy Router waits for a response from the backend application before closing the connection.

Default behavior

If the application takes too long to respond, the router returns an error (typically 504 Gateway Timeout).

Command

Correct syntax:

oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/timeout=5s

If the annotation already exists:

oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/timeout=5s \
--overwrite
Time formats
5s    = 5 seconds
30s   = 30 seconds
2m    = 2 minutes
1h    = 1 hour
Example

Suppose your application generates a large report that takes 2 minutes.

Without annotation:

Client
   |
Router (30 sec timeout)
   |
Application (120 sec)

Result:
504 Gateway Timeout

Increase timeout:

oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/timeout=2m

Now the Router waits for 2 minutes before timing out.

2. Cookie Name Annotation (Sticky Session)
Purpose

Used to enable session persistence (sticky sessions).

A user continues to communicate with the same Pod instead of being switched between different Pods.

Why is this needed?

Some applications store session data in memory.

Example:

Pod-1
Pod-2
Pod-3

User logs in.

Without sticky sessions:

Request 1 → Pod-1

Request 2 → Pod-2

Session Lost

With sticky sessions:

Request 1 → Pod-1

Request 2 → Pod-1

Request 3 → Pod-1

Everything works correctly.

Command

Correct syntax

oc annotate route myroute \
router.openshift.io/cookie_name=mycookie

Example cookie returned by browser:

Set-Cookie:
mycookie=pod1

The Router uses this cookie to send future requests to the same Pod.

3. IP Whitelist (Restricting Access)
Purpose

Allow only specific IP addresses or networks to access the Route.

Everyone else is denied.

Example

Allow only office network:

192.168.1.0/24
Command
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/ip_whitelist="192.168.1.0/24"
Multiple IPs
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/ip_whitelist="192.168.1.10 192.168.1.20"
Multiple Networks
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/ip_whitelist="192.168.1.0/24 10.10.0.0/16"
Example

Without whitelist:

Internet

User A ✓

User B ✓

User C ✓

With whitelist:

Office Network ✓

VPN Users ✓

Other Internet Users ✗

This is commonly used for:

Internal dashboards
Admin portals
Monitoring applications
Company-only applications
4. Rate Limiting
Purpose

Limits how many requests a client can send.

Helps protect applications from:

Too many requests
Bots
Brute-force attacks
Denial-of-Service (DoS) attacks
Enable Rate Limiting
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/rate-limit-connections=true
Limit Concurrent Connections

Maximum simultaneous TCP connections:

oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/rate-limit-connections.concurrent-tcp=20

Meaning:

User

Maximum Connections = 20

21st connection → Rejected
Limit HTTP Requests
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/rate-limit-connections.rate-http=100

Meaning:

Maximum 100 HTTP requests per second.

101st request

↓

Rejected or delayed
Limit TCP Connection Rate
oc annotate route myroute \
haproxy.router.openshift.io/rate-limit-connections.rate-tcp=50

Meaning:

Maximum 50 new TCP connections per second.
